# .dockerignore
# Defines what is excluded from the Docker build context.
# The build context is the set of files sent to the Docker daemon
# when running "docker build". Excluding unnecessary files:
# - Speeds up the build (less data to transfer)
# - Prevents sensitive files from accidentally entering the image
# - Reduces the chance of cache invalidation

# Gradle build cache and output directory.
# These are regenerated during the build inside the container.
# Including them would pollute the build and invalidate cache.
.gradle/
build/

# IDE configuration files — not needed in the image.
.idea/
*.iml
*.ipr
*.iws

# OS-generated metadata files — irrelevant in a Linux container.
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# Git history and configuration — not needed at runtime.
.git/
.gitignore

# Documentation — informational only, not part of the application.
README.md
README.fr.md
SECURITY.md
SECURITY.fr.md

# Environment files — sensitive credentials must never enter the image.
# The exception (.env.example) is a safe template with no real values.
.env
.env.*
!.env.example

# Docker files — the Dockerfile and Compose files are used to build
# and orchestrate containers, not needed inside the container itself.
Dockerfile
docker-compose*.yml

# Test sources — tests are skipped during Docker build (-x test).
# Excluding them reduces the build context size.
src/test/

# Log files — runtime artifacts, should not be baked into the image.
*.log
logs/